     142             : #define MIR_FLAG_LIST(_)                                                        \
     143             :     _(InWorklist)                                                               \
     144             :     _(EmittedAtUses)                                                            \
     145             :     _(Commutative)                                                              \
     146             :     _(Movable)       /* Allow passes like LICM to move this instruction */      \
     147             :     _(Lowered)       /* (Debug only) has a virtual register */                  \
     148             :     _(Guard)         /* Not removable if uses == 0 */                           \
     149             :                                                                                 \
     150             :     /* Flag an instruction to be considered as a Guard if the instructions
     151             :      * bails out on some inputs.
     152             :      *
     153             :      * Some optimizations can replace an instruction, and leave its operands
     154             :      * unused. When the type information of the operand got used as a
     155             :      * predicate of the transformation, then we have to flag the operands as
     156             :      * GuardRangeBailouts.
     157             :      *
     158             :      * This flag prevents further optimization of instructions, which
     159             :      * might remove the run-time checks (bailout conditions) used as a
     160             :      * predicate of the previous transformation.
     161             :      */                                                                         \
     162             :     _(GuardRangeBailouts)                                                       \
     163             :                                                                                 \
     164             :     /* Keep the flagged instruction in resume points and do not substitute this
     165             :      * instruction by an UndefinedValue. This might be used by call inlining
     166             :      * when a function argument is not used by the inlined instructions.
     167             :      */                                                                         \
     168             :     _(ImplicitlyUsed)                                                           \
     169             :                                                                                 \
     170             :     /* The instruction has been marked dead for lazy removal from resume
     171             :      * points.
     172             :      */                                                                         \
     173             :     _(Unused)                                                                   \
     174             :                                                                                 \
     175             :     /* When a branch is removed, the uses of multiple instructions are removed.
     176             :      * The removal of branches is based on hypotheses.  These hypotheses might
     177             :      * fail, in which case we need to bailout from the current code.
     178             :      *
     179             :      * When we implement a destructive optimization, we need to consider the
     180             :      * failing cases, and consider the fact that we might resume the execution
     181             :      * into a branch which was removed from the compiler.  As such, a
     182             :      * destructive optimization need to take into acount removed branches.
     183             :      *
     184             :      * In order to let destructive optimizations know about removed branches, we
     185             :      * have to annotate instructions with the UseRemoved flag.  This flag
     186             :      * annotates instruction which were used in removed branches.
     187             :      */                                                                         \
     188             :     _(UseRemoved)                                                               \
     189             :                                                                                 \
     190             :     /* Marks if the current instruction should go to the bailout paths instead
     191             :      * of producing code as part of the control flow.  This flag can only be set
     192             :      * on instructions which are only used by ResumePoint or by other flagged
     193             :      * instructions.
     194             :      */                                                                         \
     195             :     _(RecoveredOnBailout)                                                       \
     196             :                                                                                 \
     197             :     /* Some instructions might represent an object, but the memory of these
     198             :      * objects might be incomplete if we have not recovered all the stores which
     199             :      * were supposed to happen before. This flag is used to annotate
     200             :      * instructions which might return a pointer to a memory area which is not
     201             :      * yet fully initialized. This flag is used to ensure that stores are
     202             :      * executed before returning the value.
     203             :      */                                                                         \
     204             :     _(IncompleteObject)                                                         \

     209             :      * iterator.
     210             :      */                                                                         \

     636             :     // When a floating-point value is used by nodes which would prefer to
     637             :     // recieve integer inputs, we may be able to help by computing our result
     638             :     // into an integer directly.
     639             :     //
     640             :     // A value can be truncated in 4 differents ways:
     641             :     //   1. Ignore Infinities (x / 0 --> 0).
     642             :     //   2. Ignore overflow (INT_MIN / -1 == (INT_MAX + 1) --> INT_MIN)
     643             :     //   3. Ignore negative zeros. (-0 --> 0)
     644             :     //   4. Ignore remainder. (3 / 4 --> 0)
     645             :     //
     646             :     // Indirect truncation is used to represent that we are interested in the
     647             :     // truncated result, but only if it can safely flow into operations which
     648             :     // are computed modulo 2^32, such as (2) and (3). Infinities are not safe,
     649             :     // as they would have absorbed other math operations. Remainders are not
     650             :     // safe, as fractions can be scaled up by multiplication.
     651             :     //
     652             :     // Division is a particularly interesting node here because it covers all 4
     653             :     // cases even when its own operands are integers.
     654             :     //
     655             :     // Note that these enum values are ordered from least value-modifying to
     656             :     // most value-modifying, and code relies on this ordering.
     657             :     enum TruncateKind {
     658             :         // No correction.
     659             :         NoTruncate = 0,
     660             :         // An integer is desired, but we can't skip bailout checks.
     661             :         TruncateAfterBailouts = 1,
     662             :         // The value will be truncated after some arithmetic (see above).
     663             :         IndirectTruncate = 2,
     664             :         // Direct and infallible truncation to int32.
     665             :         Truncate = 3
     666             :     };

    1036             : // Helper class to check that GC pointers embedded in MIR instructions are in
    1037             : // in the nursery only when the store buffer has been marked as needing to
    1038             : // cancel all ion compilations. Otherwise, off-thread Ion compilation and
    1039             : // nursery GCs can happen in parallel, so it's invalid to store pointers to
    1040             : // nursery things. There's no need to root these pointers, as GC is suppressed
    1041             : // during compilation and off-thread compilations are canceled on major GCs.

    3710             : // Creates a new derived type object. At runtime, this is just a call
    3711             : // to `BinaryBlock::createDerived()`. That is, the MIR itself does not
    3712             : // compile to particularly optimized code. However, using a distinct
    3713             : // MIR for creating derived type objects allows the compiler to
    3714             : // optimize ephemeral typed objects as would be created for a
    3715             : // reference like `a.b.c` -- here, the `a.b` will create an ephemeral
    3716             : // derived type object that aliases the memory of `a` itself. The
    3717             : // specific nature of `a.b` is revealed by using
    3718             : // `MNewDerivedTypedObject` rather than `MGetProperty` or what have
    3719             : // you. Moreover, the compiler knows that there are no side-effects,
    3720             : // so `MNewDerivedTypedObject` instructions can be reordered or pruned
    3721             : // as dead code.
    3722             : class MNewDerivedTypedObject

    9975             : // All barriered operations - MCompareExchangeTypedArrayElement,
    9976             : // MExchangeTypedArrayElement, and MAtomicTypedArrayElementBinop, as
    9977             : // well as MLoadUnboxedScalar and MStoreUnboxedScalar when they are
    9978             : // marked as requiring a memory barrer - have the following
    9979             : // attributes:
    9980             : //
    9981             : // - Not movable
    9982             : // - Not removable
    9983             : // - Not congruent with any other instruction
    9984             : // - Effectful (they alias every TypedArray store)
    9985             : //
    9986             : // The intended effect of those constraints is to prevent all loads
    9987             : // and stores preceding the barriered operation from being moved to
    9988             : // after the barriered operation, and vice versa, and to prevent the
    9989             : // barriered operation from being removed or hoisted.
    9990             : 
    9991             : enum MemoryBarrierRequirement
    9992             : {
    9993             :     DoesNotRequireMemoryBarrier,
    9994             :     DoesRequireMemoryBarrier
    9995             : };
    9996             : 
    9997             : // Also see comments at MMemoryBarrierRequirement, above.
